// Sutra tensor operations — general-purpose linear algebra.
//
// Per Emma 2026-05-01: bind/unbind/bundle/similarity are
// VSA-specific; this file demonstrates the *general* tensor
// primitives the language exposes on top of the runtime
// (numpy/torch).
//
// Both PascalCase and snake_case names are accepted; both forms
// route to the same _VSA runtime method. Either style works:
//
//     vector y = Tensor.MatrixMul(M, x);    // preferred
//     vector y = Tensor.matmul(M, x);       // also works

// MatrixMul — matrix-vector multiply for the 2-D-times-1-D case.
// In a real program M would come from a learned matrix or a
// rotation primitive; here we just want to demonstrate the call.
function vector matvec(vector M, vector x) {
    return Tensor.MatrixMul(M, x);
}

// TensorProduct — Kronecker product. Two 1-D vectors produce a
// 1-D result of length n*m holding every pairwise product.
function vector kron_demo(vector a, vector b) {
    return Tensor.TensorProduct(a, b);
}

// Outer — vector outer product. Two 1-D vectors of lengths n, m
// produce a 2-D matrix of shape (n, m).
function vector outer_demo(vector a, vector b) {
    return Tensor.Outer(a, b);
}

// Dot — inner product, scalar result. Same as `Tensor.dot(a, b)`.
function scalar dot_demo(vector a, vector b) {
    return Tensor.Dot(a, b);
}

// Transpose — row/column swap. Identity on 1-D input.
function vector transpose_demo(vector m) {
    return Tensor.Transpose(m);
}
